The table describes the ranges of approximations that are hard, when parametrized in terms of c𝑐c (second and third column) or log⁡(s/d)/log⁡(c​s/d)𝑠𝑑𝑐𝑠𝑑\log(s/d)/\log(cs/d) ratio (fourth and fifth column).
Any algorithm for subquadratic join, which overlap with these ranges, would contradict the OVP.
The permissible approximations are those ranges for which truly subquadratic algorithms are known.
The upper bounds cited to [29] use fast matrix multiplication, whereas the rest don’t and are usable as data structures.
The bounds not cited elsewhere are new in this paper, though we are aware that other people have noted the hardness of signed {−1,1}11\{-1,1\} join and the data structure for {0,1}01\{0,1\} join.

The {−1,1}dsuperscript11𝑑\{-1,1\}^{d} case seems to be harder than the {0,1}dsuperscript01𝑑\{0,1\}^{d} case.
In fact Valiant [51] reduces the general case of P,Q⊆ℝd𝑃𝑄superscriptℝ𝑑P,Q\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{d} to the case P,Q⊆{−1,1}d𝑃𝑄superscript11𝑑P,Q\subseteq\{-1,1\}^{d} using the Charikar hyperplane LSH [15].
Another piece of evidence is that we can achive runtime n1+log⁡(s/d)log⁡(c​s/d)superscript𝑛1𝑠𝑑𝑐𝑠𝑑n^{1+\frac{\log(s/d)}{\log(cs/d)}} using LSH for {0,1}dsuperscript01𝑑\{0,1\}^{d}, but it is not known to be possible for {−1,1}dsuperscript11𝑑\{-1,1\}^{d}.
Furthermore there appears to be some hope for even better data dependent LSH, as we show in section 4.2.
The {0,1}dsuperscript01𝑑\{0,1\}^{d} case is particularly interesting, as it is occurs often in practice, for example when the vectors represent sets.
A better understanding of the upper and lower bounds for this case is a nice open problem.
For an ellaborate comparison of the different upper and lower bounds, see Table 1.
